Most anybody can own small patches of timber, and that's the ones that count.

Now, friends, I was talking a few minutes ago about the importance of the small woodlands.
That's the small patches of wood.
You know, I knew a couple one time.
They were friends of mine.
He was a farmer, and he and his wife had a nice place.
And I heard that he'd had an accident.
Well, the whole thing is I felt pretty good over the thing after it turned out like it did.
But the man had had an accident.
He was building a new barn.
And he was putting a roof on, and it fell off and laid himself up.
So I went by to see how he was getting along.
Sure enough, he was.
He was laid up there with a broke leg and falling off this barn.
And he and his wife was having a little argument when I come in, but there wasn't much he could do because he was laying up there flat of his back and didn't feel too good, you know.
But it seemed like that she had...
got a quick price on some timber they had.
They had a 48-acre patch of timber, and I mean it was really nice.
And he had just gone to the expense of building this barn and everything, and cash was kind of low, and they needed quick money.
So she had jumped out there and got a quick price on all of this nice timber on this 48-acre patch of wood.
Well, the old man, he is plenty sore about it.
He just couldn't see it.

All he could picture, you know, of this timber that he'd taken care of and was proud of it, and all he could visualize was all that nice timber cut off of this land, and he just couldn't stand the idea.
